{{Infobox football biography | name = Grady Diangana | fullname = Grady Diangana<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.premierleague.com/news/844127|title=2018/19 Premier League squads confirmed|publisher=Premier League |date=3 September 2018 |accessdate=28 December 2018}}</ref> | image = Grady Diangana - December 2018.jpg | image_size = 160 | caption = Diangana in 2018 | birth_place = [[Democratic Republic of Congo]] | birth_date = {{birth date and age|1998|4|19|df=y}}<ref name=whprofile>{{cite web|url=https://www.whufc.com/teams/first-team/squad/grady-diangana|title=Grady Diangana| publisher=West Ham United F.C.|accessdate=5 February 2019}}</ref> | height = {{height|m=1.80}} | position = [[Midfielder]] | currentclub = [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]] | clubnumber = 45 | youthyears1 = 2010–2016 | youthclubs1 = [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]] | years1 = 2016– | clubs1 = [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]] | caps1 = 14 | goals1 = 0 | club-update = 27 February 2019 (UTC) | nationalyears1 = 2018– | nationalteam1 = [[England national under-20 football team|England U20]] | nationalcaps1 = 1 | nationalgoals1 = 0 | nationalteam-update = 21:39, 27 December 2018 (UTC) }}
'''Grady Diangana''' (born 19 April 1998) is a Congolese-born English professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays for [[West Ham United]] as an [[attacking midfielder]]. He wears '''Diang ''' as his shirt name.
==Early life== Diangana was born in the [[Democratic Republic of Congo]]. His family moved to the UK when he was four years old. Diangana grew up in [[Woolwich]], London.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/sport/football/west-ham-academy-staging-a-revival-as-grady-diangana-shines-brightest-on-big-night-for-young-hammers-a3947151.html|title=West Ham academy staging a revival as Diangana shines brightest|work=London Evening Standard|accessdate=30 September 2018|date=27 September 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2018/nov/20/grady-diangana-west-ham-interview|title=West Ham’s Grady Diangana: ‘I feel I can go out there and express myself’|first=Paul|last=MacInnes|date=20 November 2018|publisher=|accessdate=19 January 2019|via=www.theguardian.com}}</ref>
==Club career== Diangana joined the [[West Ham United F.C. Under-23s and Academy|West Ham youth system]] in 2010, aged 12.<ref name=footballlondon>{{Cite web |title=Who is Grady Diangana? The West Ham youngster making his debut against Macclesfield Town |last=Johnson |first=Greg |work=football.london |date=14 September 2018 |accessdate=4 October 2018 |url= https://www.football.london/west-ham-united-fc/who-grady-diangana-west-ham-15205549}}</ref> Originally a [[Striker (association football)|striker]], he began playing as an attacking midfielder at under-15 level. He made his under-18 debut for the club in February 2014, and his [[Premier League 2]] debut in January 2015. He signed his first professional contract with the Hammers on 14 May 2016.<ref name=whprofile/> He signed a new two-year contract in June 2018.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Hammers youngster Diangana pens new two-year contract |publisher=West Ham United F.C. |date=14 June 2018 |accessdate=4 October 2018 |url= https://www.whufc.com/news/articles/2018/june/14-june/hammers-youngster-diangana-pens-new-two-year-contract}}</ref>
On 26 September 2018, Diangana made his first team debut in the [[EFL Cup]] against [[Macclesfield Town F.C.|Macclesfield Town]], playing the full game and scoring two goals in an 8–0 victory at the [[London Stadium]], in which fellow debutants [[Conor Coventry]] and [[Joe Powell (footballer, born 1998)|Joe Powell]] also featured.<ref>{{Cite web |title=West Ham 8–0 Macclesfield: Hammers thrash Macclesfield to reach fourth round |publisher=BBC Sport |date=26 September 2018 |accessdate=4 October 2018 |url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/45569334}}</ref> Three days later, Diangana made his first [[Premier League]] appearance, coming on as a 93rd minute substitute for [[Felipe Anderson]] in a 3–1 home victory against [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/45610325|title=West Ham United 3–1 Manchester United: Mourinho's side record worst start since 1989–90|date=29 September 2018|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=30 September 2018}}</ref> Diangana became a regular in the team following an injury to [[Andriy Yarmolenko]], making his first Premier League start against [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]] on 27 October and registering his first league assist in the following game, against [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=West Ham starlet Grady Diangana earns first England U20 call up |last=Inkersole |first=Sam |work=football.london |date=6 November 2018 |accessdate=26 November 2018 |url= https://www.football.london/west-ham-united-fc/players/grady-diangana-england-u20-call-15393077}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Will Diangana be West Ham's next homegrown superstar? |first=Ed |last=Dove |publisher=ESPN |date=2 November 2018 |accessdate=26 November 2018 |url= http://www.espn.co.uk/soccer/blog-football-africa/story/3687535/will-grady-diangana-be-next-off-the-west-ham-production-line}}</ref> On 18 January 2019, Diangana signed a new six-year contract that keeps him at West Ham until 2025.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Grady Diangana signs new long-term West Ham contract |publisher=West Ham United F.C. |date=18 January 2019 |accessdate=19 January 2019 |url= https://www.whufc.com/news/articles/2019/january/18-january/grady-diangana-signs-new-long-term-west-ham-contract}}</ref>
==International career== In November 2018, Diangana received his first international call-up, for [[England national under-20 football team|England U20]], for a game against [[Germany national under-20 football team|Germany U20]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.whufc.com/news/articles/2018/november/09-november/diangana-earns-first-england-u20s-call|title=Diangana earns first England U20s call-up|publisher=West Ham United F.C.|date=9 November 2018|accessdate=9 November 2018}}</ref> He made his England debut on 19 November in a 2–0 win against Germany with a performance described as both "dazzling" and "tremendous".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.whufc.com/news/articles/2018/november/19-november/diangana-dazzles-england-debut-victory|title=Diangana dazzles in England debut victory|publisher=West Ham United F.C.|date=19 November 2018|accessdate=26 November 2018}}</ref>
==Style of play== Diangana generally plays as a right-sided attacking midfielder but can play across the forward line. He cites [[Ronaldinho]] as an influence.<ref name=footballlondon/>
==Career statistics== {{Updated|match played 27 February 2019}}
